        <p>The name <mark>"ping-pong"</mark> was in wide use before British manufacturer <mark>J. Jaques & Son Ltd</mark> trademarked it in 1901. The name
        "ping-pong" then came to describe the game played using the rather expensive Jaques's equipment, with other
        manufacturers calling it table tennis. A similar situation arose in the <mark>United States</mark>, where Jaques sold the rights to
        the "ping-pong" name to Parker Brothers. <mark>Parker Brothers</mark> then enforced its trademark for the term in the 1920s, making
        the various associations change their names to "<mark>table tennis</mark>" instead of the more common, but trademarked, term. The
        U.S. trademark for "Ping-Pong" is currently owned by Indian Industries, Inc.<mark> Escalade Sports</mark>.</p>
